    "body": "### Problem\n\nI'm not sure this qualifies as a bug, but that's at best an unexpected behaviour.\n\nWhen running neovim with `vim.opt.exrc = true`, and a `.nvim.lua` in my folder, everything loads as expected.\nHowever, when running neovim as a server with `neovim --listen 0.0.0.0:4444`, `exrc` is ignored and `.nvim.lua` is not sourced.\nI suspect this has to do with the safety measure that requires user confirmation to accept loading the lua file.\n\n```\n/home/arnaud/devel/diy/cat_tracker/.nvim.lua is not trusted.                                                                                     \n[i]gnore, (v)iew, (d)eny, (a)llow: \n```\n\nI'm using this feature in a few embeded development projects (ESP32) to set some custom LSP configuration (C++ cross-compilation). In order to make this setup reproducible, everything runs within devcontainers and I'm connecting remotely to the nvim server within the devcontainer. Not having the custom configuration taken into account prevents the LSP to work in this environment.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nCreate a `.nvim.lua` with a simple print\n```lua\nprint('.nvim.lua was sourced')\n```\n\nRun nvim in this folder with `nvim --listen 0.0.0.0:4444`, the message does not show.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nHonour `exrc` configuration and load the custom configuration `.nvim.lua` (and related naming conventions)\n\nIs there a way to achieve this?\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.10.1\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nnot relevant\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nubuntu 24.04\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nxterm-kitty\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-kitty\n\n### Installation\n\nAppImage",
